{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17475228","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17475228"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:30:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:30:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12572"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12572","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12572"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.3,0.59,0.05,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5071"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108434"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5071"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12572"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90824"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"156"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"2308"},{"type":"tags","id":"2443"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"12916"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8474"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8645"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12291"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13675"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14673"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41765"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108434"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn eight-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a one-day history of fever, headache, vomiting, and irritability. His parents report that he has not been eating well. He is now complaining of blurred vision and appears confused. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears lethargic with neck stiffness. His temperature is 39.2\u00b0C, pulse rate 120/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 26/min, and SpO2 98% on room air. Forceful flexion of his neck causes involuntary flexion of the hips and knees.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT brain","Lumbar puncture","Commence intravenous antibiotic therapy","Intravenous fluid bolus","MRI brain"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis eight-year-old boy presents with signs and symptoms highly suggestive of meningitis, including fever, headache, vomiting, irritability, and neck stiffness. The presence of confusion and visual disturbance raises concern for raised intracranial pressure (ICP). In this setting, the most appropriate next step is to \u003Cstrong\u003Ecommence intravenous antibiotic therapy\u003C/strong\u003E immediately, even before performing a lumbar puncture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile blood cultures should certainly be obtained before starting antibiotics, they should not delay treatment if the patient is critically ill, as in this case. Delaying antibiotic administration in a patient with suspected meningitis and signs of raised ICP could lead to life-threatening complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous fluid bolus\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered as part of the initial management, especially if there are signs of shock. However, in this case, with signs of raised ICP, careful fluid management is crucial, and antibiotic therapy takes precedence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELumbar puncture (LP)\u003C/strong\u003E is typically the diagnostic test of choice in suspected meningitis. However, it is contraindicated in the presence of raised ICP due to the risk of brain herniation. Signs of increased ICP to look out for include diplopia (which may present as blurred vision as was noted in this case), abnormal pupillary responses, decerebrate or decorticate posture, bradycardia with hypertension, irregular respirations or papilloedema. Other contraindications to LP include infection at the puncture site, coagulopathy, spinal cord tumours, and allergy to local anaesthetics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ECT brain\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered prior to LP in patients with suspected meningitis and high risk of cerebral herniation. However, given this patient\u0027s symptoms suggestive of significantly raised ICP, empiric antibiotic treatment should be prioritized over delaying therapy for imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI brain\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered if encephalitis is suspected, as it can provide more detailed imaging of brain tissue. However, like CT, it should not delay the initiation of antibiotics in a case of suspected meningitis with signs of raised ICP. MRI can be performed later in the course of treatment if needed for further evaluation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMeningitis in this age group is commonly caused by \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003ENeisseria meningitidis\u003C/em\u003E. Prompt initiation of appropriate antibiotics is crucial in reducing morbidity and mortality associated with bacterial meningitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Immediate commencement of antibiotic therapy in suspected meningitis should be undertaken prior to investigations if there are signs of raised intracranial pressure.","Blood cultures should be obtained before starting antibiotics in suspected meningitis, but should not delay treatment if the patient is critically ill."],"references":["Hersi K, Gonzalez FJ, Kondamudi NP. Meningitis. [Updated 2022 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [online]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459360/","Lumbar puncture guideline. In: The Royal Children\u2019s Hospital Melbourne \u2013 Clinical Practice Guidelines [online]. Accessed 2025 Jun 25. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/lumbar_puncture_guideline/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90824"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12572"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90824","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90824"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-11T15:05:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-01T10:18:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5071"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108434"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"em